            "format": "text/html",
            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>LD.III.R4</em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Interview between Clennam and Dorrit [...]</strong></p>\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-5260f247-7fff-83d7-b134-07511459f246\">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Clennam invites Dorrit to walk with him on this bridge, &ldquo;where there is an escape from the noise of the street&rdquo; (LD 91). His goal is to learn about the origin of the connection between her and his mother. It is in writing this interview that Dickens begins occasionally writing &ldquo;Little Dorrit&rdquo; (although not consistently) in the manuscript. The first usage is right after the pair arrive on the Iron Bridge, when Dickens crosses out the first two letters of Dorrit (&ldquo;Do&rdquo;) and begins the sentence again: &ldquo;Little Dorrit seemed the least, the quietest, the weakest of Heaven&rsquo;s creatures&rdquo; (LD 93). He will return to using &ldquo;Dorrit&rdquo; but soon add the &ldquo;Little&rdquo; more consistently, especially after Maggy&rsquo;s arrival and her use of the term &ldquo;Little Mother&rdquo; (95).</p>"
        }
    ],
